\begin_layout Standard
You may Combine Actions to attack or defend, move, or accomplish other tasks
 given appropriate descriptions according to the Primary Rule
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Primary Rule!Combining Abilities
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 A Combined Action might be a super-strong character throwing another character
 who attacks with his fists or blades (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Fastball Special
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) or two martial artist coordinating their attacks (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

You go high, I'll go low
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) or one character grabbing a enemy to hold him long enough for another
 to hit.
 A squad of riflemen might combine all their shots into a single attack.
 When Combining Abilities the combo becomes a single attack, and the Combined
 Power Level is equal to the Power Level of one of the Combined Abilities
 of the attacker’s choice, plus 1 
\shape italic
Point
\shape default
 for each 
\shape italic
character
\shape default
 Combining, to a maximum plus equal to 
\emph on
the number of players in the fight
\emph default
.
 Thus, each player at the table involved in the fight can contribute, if
 they choose, but you can never get a bigger plus than that.
 enemies face the same limit: the number of 
\emph on
players
\emph default
, not the number of enemies.
 (Limiting the maximum to the number of players actually involved in the
 fight means that characters aren't penalized for having a big group of
 players who are off doing something else while the enemies ambush them.)
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Advantages of the Combined Action will be those of the Ability that's
 chosen as the base for the Action; you cannot mix and match the Advantages
 of the different Abilities.
 Disadvantages are applied separately.
 Using a Ability as part of Combining Abilities costs an Action, even if
 it's an Automatic Power.
\end_layout

