\begin_layout Chapter
Research
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Science and engineering form core elements of Science Fiction stories, so
 it's not surprising that many protagonists are scientists or engineers
 and are constantly doing research or tinkering with devices.
 In Zap!
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

characters with the Scientist Template can do Research Scenes to revise
 and expand their Science!
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Power to the needs of the adventure, but that's just one way that research
 into new technology, devices, and scientific knowledge can come into play.
 Characters may also perform Research to gain new Assets and improve upon
 their existing ones.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once each session, characters may perform a Research scene using any appropriate
 Ability (the Scientist's Scientific Research Shtick, or any science or
 engineering Shtick that characters using other Templates may have).
 The characters choose an Asset (see
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Assets"

\end_inset

) that they want to improve upon with research and tinkering, or a new Asset
 they want to create.
 The Difficulty for the Research is the PL of the Asset.
 Scoring a success grants 1 XP for improving that Asset, or towards its
 purchase for a new one; if the 1 XP from success isn't enough to buy the
 improvement or new Asset immediately, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bank
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 it as belonging to that particular Asset.
 When making a Research roll, always check for a Mishap even if the Power
 doesn't have a Disadvantage that would call for a check.
 If a Mishap occurs, the GM should invent something interesting that went
 wrong, such as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Shower of sparks, some piece of equipment is broken.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Small explosion; treat as a single attack on the researcher(s) at the PL
 of the Asset.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Line of Research is set back, if any XP was accumulated on this Research
 lose 1 XP.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Experiment sets off an adventure.
 Perhaps the researcher is split into a good version and a bad version,
 or it attracts a mischievous or hostile entity through a spacio-temporal
 rift, or the ship is hurtled back in time or to a different quadrant of
 the galaxy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Sudden insight.
 You can abandon this Research and put any XP already banked into a new
 line of Research, aiming at a new Asset.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Serendipity! You've accidentally discovered something else entirely.
 GM grants you a Major Asset of her design.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Interesting
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in this context means that it has some effect on the game besides just
 the description of colored lights and things blowing up, although that
 effect need not have mechanics attached.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A new Minor Asset costs 1 XP; Major Assets that belong to the players jointly
 cost 3 XP; Major Assets that belong to a particular character cost as many
 XP as that character has Boosts.
 Improving Assets costs as many XP as the Asset has in Boosts.
 A Minor Asset is generally something like a piece of equipment: the PL
 is the die-size.
 A Major Asset is generally something that's treated almost as a character,
 like a Vehicle, Base, or Companion, with its own Attributes and Abilities.
 The GM should determine what the Attributes and Abilities of a new Major
 Asset are, following the description by the players of what they're trying
 to Research.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When playing out a Research Scene, players are strongly encouraged to describe
 what they're doing in some detail, even if it's just techno-babble, and
 try their to fit the science and technology into the setting and tone,
 whether that's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I'm adjusting the baryon filters on the warp core to reverse the polarity
 of the tachyon flow, which if it works should let us create a short-term
 temporal rift so we can travel back in time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I'm duct-taping a grenade launcher and a flame-thrower to my pulse rifle.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Players can combine their Abilities, and should add to the description:
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I'll be monitoring the efficiency of the baryon filters using my Radar Vision
 prosthesis, to warn if the filters are becoming unstable.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the campaign is using Wealth, you can substitute WP for any expenditure
 of research XP; you can even use Research to generate WP by inventing new
 processes or gizmos that you can sell or patent.
 The difficulty of getting a Wealth Point via Research is your current Wealth
 PL, with the usual results for Research Mishaps.
\end_layout

